Storage gateway, the hybrid bridge.

Storage gateway runs as a virtual machine or hardware appliance in your on-premises data center and presents AWS storage as local storage to on-premises systems. There are four flavors, distinguished by what they expose locally and what backs them in AWS.

The file gateway exposes a file share over the standard network protocols and lands files directly in object storage. A second file gateway variant fronts the Windows file server as a remote-office cache. The volume gateway exposes block storage over the i-scuzzy protocol, in two modes: stored keeps the full dataset locally with asynchronous backup to the cloud, while cached keeps the primary copy in the cloud with only hot data on-premises. And the tape gateway presents a virtual tape library to replace physical tape, leaving your backup software unchanged.

The two splits to internalize are file versus block, the same as object versus block storage with the gateway as translator, and stored versus cached, which is about where the full dataset lives.
